  "body": "\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏  ͏ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­ ­  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Sunday Supplement: Cryonics And Education [https://thebrowser.com/r/bbea39ac?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nBy Sylvia Bishop • 26 Apr 2026\r\n\r\n\r\nView in browser [https://thebrowser.com/r/793da21a?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nView in browser [https://thebrowser.com/r/65404e98?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nDear readers — we are collecting stories of Browser recommendations that have stuck in people’s minds over the years. Let us know [https://thebrowser.com/r/8fe0528c?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd] about an article you still think about; our favourite will win a Browser mug. Many thanks for the delightful submissions so far! — Ed.\r\n\r\nFrom The Browser 10 years ago:\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat If Cryonics Works? [https://thebrowser.com/r/2df1cf5d?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\n\r\nRachel Nuwer | BBC | 25th April 2016\r\n\r\nWhat if cryonics works, and frozen people come back to life decades or centuries later? “Dislocated in time, alienated from society and coming to grips with the certainty that everyone and everything they had ever known is irretrievably lost, they would likely suffer symptoms of intense trauma. And that’s not to mention the fact that some may have to deal with a whole new body because only their head was preserved“ (2,050 words [https://thebrowser.com/r/8e04cda4?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd])\r\n\r\nFrom The Browser 8 Years Ago:\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Case Against Education [https://thebrowser.com/r/767a239b?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\n\r\nScott Aaronson | Shtetl-Optimized | 26th April 2018\r\n\r\nDiscussion of Bryan Caplan’s argument that higher education is mostly about signalling, not about learning. “Employers want smart workers who will also show up on time, turn in the work they’re supposed to, and jump through whatever hoops authorities put in front of them. The main purpose of school, over and above certifying intelligence, is to serve as a hugely costly and time-consuming — and therefore reliable — signal that the graduates are conscientious conformists” (4,900 words [https://thebrowser.com/r/975d4132?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd])\r\n\r\n----------------------------------------\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\nQuestion Of The Week\r\n\r\nThis week, we recommended Patrick K Lin’s Surveillance Pricing [https://thebrowser.com/r/574f2675?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]. He describes companies using personal data to calculate personalised prices, and argues against free-speech-based protection of data flows. What did Browser users make of this?\r\n\r\n(a) Personalised data-based pricing is bad, and should be prohibited by law\r\n(b) Personalised data-based pricing is bad, but legal prohibitions create worse issues\r\n(c) Personalised data-based pricing is not bad\r\n\r\nVote now! [https://thebrowser.com/r/d2423207?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\n\r\nLast week’s question\r\n\r\nWe shared Henrik Karlsson’s Hacker Mindset, [https://thebrowser.com/r/78c93024?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd] in which he cites examples of people who play systems in unconventional ways: “There is a superficial system which pretends to be made of one thing... But actually, it is really made of something else... And if you learn to understand that underlying system, you can find ways to use the lower-level details to steer the system in a way that looks incomprehensible to those who only see the more superficial system.”\r\n\r\n> Have Browser readers experienced or witnessed successes — or failures — from this kind of thinking? We'd love to hear about it!\r\n\r\nA perfect bijou mailbag [https://thebrowser.com/r/25618964?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd] this week — one for and one against, hinging on whether the ‘hacker mindset’ concept captured anything worth noting. Thanks to our two readers for flying the two flags!\r\n\r\n----------------------------------------\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\nPerformance Of The Week\r\n\r\nNPR Tiny Desk Concert| Amaia | 22.04 [https://thebrowser.com/r/a1946345?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n[https://thebrowser.com/r/f1db03c2?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCompelling and full of small surprises throughout, with unexpected turns in rhythm or timbre — this is a songwriter who keeps you guessing. Even in the final bars of her set, she evokes a smile with one last new sound.\r\n\r\n----------------------------------------\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\nBook Of The Week\r\n\r\nThe Art Of Political Murder | Francisco Goldman [https://thebrowser.com/r/60bbdca4?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\n\r\nRecommended by David Grann at Five Books: [https://thebrowser.com/r/699e6fe1?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\n\r\n“It’s set in Guatemala at a time when there was great repression from the military regime and dissidents were hunted down and killed. These were really genocidal crimes. One of the most infamous killings was of Bishop Juan Gerardi, who had spoken out against the regime and in defence of the victims... Goldman’s case shows how, when there is a political killing, when there is a criminal power structure involved, you can corrupt the organs of justice and subvert any sense of truth... The murkiness of the case, the knottiness of it, is extreme; Goldman lets you get a sense of what it’s like to be in a sea of these counter-narratives with everyone spinning a different version in order to cover up the real truth.“\r\n\r\n----------------------------------------\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\nQuiz Of The Week\r\n\r\nYou may have internalised that stalagmites grow up while stalactites hang down, and learned to tell your escarpment from your promontory. Or perhaps you zoned out from these lessons, and still divide the world into ‘hill’, ‘not hill’ and ‘weird pointy feature’... This week, how many of these lesser-known geographical features can you define?\r\n\r\n(i) Brinicle\r\n(ii) Yardang\r\n(iii) Pingo\r\n(iv) Snottite\r\n(v) Hoodoo\r\n(vi) Stastrugi\r\n(vii) Esker\r\n\r\nAnswers below, after the poem\r\n\r\n----------------------------------------\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\nImage Of The Week\r\n\r\nLa Balayeuse | Pieter Janssens Elinga | 1670 [https://thebrowser.com/r/305416e5?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\n\r\nA slice of life — little-known Janssens treats his interiors “like still life“, according to the (translated) Paris De Musees. Copies of this painting also exist in the Hermitage Museum, St Petersburg and the Louvre, Paris. The eight close up views available [https://thebrowser.com/r/c8fbe3e0?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd] are recommended to appreciate the detail, including the maid’s face in the mirror opposite her.\r\n\r\n----------------------------------------\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\nPoem Of The Week\r\n\r\nThe God Who Loves You | Carl Dennis [https://thebrowser.com/r/d324a510?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\nOn relating to the lives we might have lived. Moving.\r\n\r\n> It must be troubling for the god who loves you   \r\n> To ponder how much happier you’d be today   \r\n> Had you been able to glimpse your many futures...\r\n\r\nRead The God Who Loves You [https://thebrowser.com/r/d7ca2cc2?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd] and more by Carl Dennis [https://thebrowser.com/r/71fe4551?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd] at Poetry Foundation\r\n\r\n----------------------------------------\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nhttps://thebrowser.com/r/3e5664fa?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd\r\n\r\nhttps://thebrowser.com/r/9b3a5569?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd\r\n\r\n\r\nQuiz Answers\r\n\r\n(i) Brinicle [https://thebrowser.com/r/66681094?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd] — “a descending tube that projects downward from floating sea ice on the surface of the ocean“ formed of brine\r\n(ii) Yardang [https://thebrowser.com/r/eeba49af?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd] — “An elongated erosional landform, commonly found in deserts, resembling the hull of an inverted boat.“\r\n(iii) Pingo [https://thebrowser.com/r/fd1325df?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd] — dome-shaped hills found in periglacial environments\r\n(iv) Snottite [https://thebrowser.com/r/afbad136?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]— a bacterial stalactite found in caves\r\n(v) Hoodoo [https://thebrowser.com/r/5c54f59c?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd] — “a spire made of rock and minerals that can range anywhere from five to one hundred and fifty feet tall“ created by erosion\r\n(vi) Stastrugi [https://thebrowser.com/r/c2ec5e90?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]— “form much as sand dunes in the desert, when small grains of snow drift together in a strong wind and then freeze solid, forming hard ridges on the surface of the snow.“\r\n(vii) Esker [https://thebrowser.com/r/a40fc630?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd] — “ridges made of sands and gravels, deposited by glacial meltwater“\r\n\r\n----------------------------------------\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nGift The Browser To A Friend [https://thebrowser.com/r/a37375b5?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\n\r\n----------------------------------------\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nShortcode Glossary:\r\nU = Ungated, free. M = Metered paywall. B = Metered paywall can be bypassed using private/incognito browsing. Full details of our shortcodes here [https://thebrowser.com/r/2eafa092?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd].\r\n\r\n----------------------------------------\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nThis post is only for paying subscribers of The Browser [https://thebrowser.com/r/4b0f7fb7?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd], but please do forward it to any friends who deserve a treat today, especially if you think they might be interested in becoming Browser subscribers in the future.\r\n\r\nCaroline Crampton, Editor-In-Chief; Robert Cottrell, Founding Editor; Jodi Ettenberg, Editor-At-Large; Dan Feyer, Crossword Editor; Uri Bram, CEO & Publisher; Sylvia Bishop, Assistant Publisher; Al Breach, Founding Director\r\n\r\nEditorial comments and letters to the editor: editor@thebrowser.com [https://thebrowser.com/r/030a1618?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\nTechnical issues and support requests: support@thebrowser.com [https://thebrowser.com/r/a80b8344?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\nOr write at any time to the publisher: uri@thebrowser.com [https://thebrowser.com/r/7cc24fb2?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd]\r\n\r\nElsewhere on The Browser, and of possible interest to Browser subscribers: Letters To The Editor [https://thebrowser.com/r/774ee9a0?m=870013e5-9af6-40f5-bf0e-51ce412162bd], where you will find constructive comment from fellow-subscribers; The Reader [https://thebrowser.com/r/381e